<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by Victor KM:
[I]Ok, the people in this thread who have stated that FF7 is a non-linear RPG have some kind of deficiency or something.  The definition of Linear is you have to do actions 1, leading to action 2, leading to action 3, and so on, leading to the goal you are trying to accomplish.

If FF7 had been non-linear, you would have been able to get the airship in the first 5 minutes of the game, and you cannot even leave the city for the first couple hours.  The fact is, in 7, you have to meet each goal before you can meet the next.  Of course there are side quests such as the golden chocobo and the weapons, but when you boil it down you move in a straight line the whole game.

In a non-linear game, you can do whatever you want.  You can kill every single NPC in the whole game and still be able to finish.  You can fight the final boss whenever you feel you are ready, and depending on your other actions, you can get whatever ending you deserve. 

A good example of this is Chrono Trigger for the SNES.  You are able to fight Lavos as soon as you have access to the halls of time or whatever, and beat the game, but if you do, you miss out on a lot of stuff.  You can play all the different areas in different orders, and it only affects the end of the game.  Same with Chrono Cross.  Those two are the epitome of non-linear console games.

As for PC games, Fall-out 1 and 2 are very non-linear, as you can beat the game without playing most of it and can pretty much do as you like.  Divinity is also very non-linear, to an extent.  There are so many things you can so at any one time, and its great.  But you still have to go into the castle, and find all 7 of the council members or whatever, in order to win.  You can't just try and kill Janus the first time you go into the castle, or anything like that though.

But to sum up my post, FF7 is quite Linear.  Thank you.[/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
